\begin_layout Paragraph*
Clarification: Unentangled vs.
 product states.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In conventional quantum mechanics, using the real and complex numbers, a
 state is unentangled when it can be expressed as a product state or when
 equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(27) reports its purity to be 1.
 When using finite fields, it is possible for equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(27) to produce a purity of 1 for some entangled states.
 For example, consider the normalized 3-qubit state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\Psi_{0}}$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\ff{7^{2}}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ket{\Psi_{0}}=\ket{011}+\left(-2-\rmi\right)\ket{100}+\ket{101}+\ket{110}\textrm{ .}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, in finite fields, the simplest way to calculate the number of unentangled
 states is to ignore equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(27) and to count the number of product states.
 This is exactly how the counting in section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

5.4 was produced, but the paper did not clarify that counting using equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(27) would be incorrect.
\end_layout

