\begin_layout Subsection
Maximal entanglement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In conventional quantum mechanics, a state is maximally entangled when equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(27) reports its purity to be 0.
 In the discrete case, states whose purity is a multiple of the field characteri
stic are incorrectly labeled as maximally entangled.
 For example, consider the normalized 3-qubit product state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\Psi_{1}}$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\ff{3^{2}}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ket{\Psi_{1}}=\ket{0}\otimes\left(\ket{0}-\ket{1}\right)\otimes\left(\ket{0}-\ket{1}\right)\textrm{ .}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\Psi_{1}}$
\end_inset

 has the purity 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{P_{\fh}}=0$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{P_{\fh}}=\sum_{j=1}^{n}\sum_{\mu=x,y,z}\left\langle \sigma_{\mu}^{j}\right\rangle ^{2}
\]

\end_inset

is equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(27) eliminating the 
\begin_inset Formula $1/n$
\end_inset

 factor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In continuous case, the zero purity actually means every summand is 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\forall j,\forall\mu,\braket{\sigma_{\mu}^{j}}=0\textrm{ .}\label{eq:john}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Because equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:john"

\end_inset

) avoids any wrapping around when adding expectation values, it defines
 maximally entangled states over finite fields.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Computing some examples for various 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and small values of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, one can verify explicitly that unit-norm product states for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\{3,7,11,19,\ldots\}$
\end_inset

 occur with frequency 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(p+1)p^{2}(p-1)^{2}=\{144,14\,112,145\,200,2339\,280,\ldots\}\ ,
\]

\end_inset

and for general 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(p+1)p^{n}(p-1)^{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The irreducible state counts are reduced by 
\begin_inset Formula $(p+1)$
\end_inset

, giving 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p^{2}(p-1)^{2}=\{36,1764,12\,100,116\,964,\ldots\}\ ,
\]

\end_inset

and in general for 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-qubits, there are 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}\left(p-1\right)^{n}$
\end_inset

 instances of product pure states.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Repeating the computation, we find maximally entanglement states with frequencie
s for two qubits of 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\left(p-1\right)\left(p+1\right)^{2}=\left\{ 96,2688,15\,840,136\,800,\ldots\right\} \ .
\]

\end_inset

The irreducible state counts for maximal entanglement are reduced by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(p+1\right)$
\end_inset

, giving for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\left(p^{2}-1\right)=\left\{ 24,336,1320,6840,\ldots\right\} \ .
\]

\end_inset

For three-qubits, there are 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{3}\left(p^{4}-1\right)\left(p+1\right)$
\end_inset

 instances of pure maximally entangled states, while the general formula
 for four-qubit states remains unclear.
\end_layout

